Feature Design: Execution Feedback Loop                                                                            
                                                        
 Context

 AgentHandover's pipeline is currently one-directional: observe user -> generate Skill -> serve to agent -> done.
 The system has no visibility into what happens after an agent fetches a Skill. This feature closes the loop so
 that execution outcomes (success, deviation, failure) flow back and improve Skills over time.

 Existing foundation (already built):
 - ExecutionMonitor class with full lifecycle: start, step, complete, fail, abort, history, success_rate
 - Trigger file handlers in main.py (lines 3455-3607) for execution-start/step/complete
 - Execution feedback already updates procedure staleness.drift_signals and staleness.last_confirmed (main.py lines
  3548-3599)
 - EscalationHandler already handles 3+ failures -> demotion
 - QueryAPIServer already accepts execution_monitor parameter

 What's missing:
 - MCP tools for agents to report execution (currently requires filesystem access via trigger files)
 - REST API endpoints for non-MCP agents
 - Observation-based passive verification (watching the screen during agent execution)
 - Systematic Skill improvement from execution data (branches, timing, confidence)
 - One-click agent pairing in the SwiftUI app
 - Execution progress/results UI in menu bar

